TY  - JOUR
AU  - Qi, Yingjie
T1  - Big broad banks: how does cross-selling affect lending?
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfad028
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
SP  - 551
EP  - 592
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - This article investigates how cross-selling affects relationship lending using internal data from a large bank and the Swedish credit registry. I show that within a bank–firm relationship, profit earned from non-loan products cross-subsidizes loans and increases (1) credit supply and (2) the likelihood of the bank’s pausing or waiving interest payments for delinquent loans (lenience in delinquency). For identification, I exploit the Basel II-induced exogenous variation in products’ profitability while holding constant the firm’s creditworthiness and relationship informativeness. I find that the average affected firm experienced a decrease of 6 percent ($400,000) in credit supply and 30 percent (9.8 pp) in lenience in delinquency. The results highlight the importance of cross-subsidization as a mechanism through which cross-selling affects bank–firm relationships and inform optimal regulatory design for lenders who multi-produce.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfad028
ER  - 



